<subSubSection id="7C9121BF1726A90998CCFC667C6AFB23" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="343472341726A90998CCFC667C6AFB23" blockId="23.[151,1436,901,1247]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis id="06FFAE261726A90998CCFC66797CFC3B" bold="true" box="[198,319,941,967]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Remarks.</emphasis>
The proepisternal setal warts are absent, like in most 
<taxonomicName id="F38B09B71726A9099BBEFC667CFDFC3B" box="[948,1214,941,967]" class="Insecta" family="Hydropsychidae" genus="Hydromanicus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="06FFAE261726A9099BBEFC667C1CFC3A" box="[948,1119,941,966]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Hydromanicus</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
; the median cell of the forewings is open; crossvein m-cu in the forewings is present; and only fork 1 is lost in the hind wings. According to these primary generic characters this species belongs in the genus 
<taxonomicName id="F38B09B71726A9099C50FC367D46FBEA" box="[1114,1285,1021,1046]" class="Insecta" family="Hydropsychidae" genus="Hydromanicus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="06FFAE261726A9099C50FC367D46FBEA" box="[1114,1285,1021,1046]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Hydromanicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Although a minute fork is present in 
<bibRefCitation id="501A0FC51726A90999CAFBEE7A35FBC3" author="Ulmer, G." box="[448,630,1061,1087]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="41 - 54" refId="ref113333" refString="Ulmer, G. (1910) Trichoptera. In: The Percy Slades Trust Expedition to the Indian Ocean in 1905, vol. III. Transactions of the Linnean Society of London, (2. serial zoology), 14 (1), 41 - 54." type="journal article" year="1910">Ulmer’s (1910)</bibRefCitation>
original description and drawing, no fork was detected in the specimens studied in this work. 
<bibRefCitation id="501A0FC51726A90999DFFB867A24FB9B" author="Scott, K. M. F." box="[469,615,1101,1127]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="299 - 422" refId="ref112613" refString="Scott, K. M. F. (1983) On the Hydropsychidae (Trichoptera) of Southern Africa with keys to African genera of imagos, larvae and pupae and species lists. Annals of the Cape Province Museum (natural History), 14 (8), 299 - 422." type="journal article" year="1983">Scott (1983)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="501A0FC51726A9099AABFB867B1BFB9B" author="Schefter, P. W." box="[673,856,1101,1127]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="133 - 154" refId="ref111953" refString="Schefter, P. W. (2005) Re-evaluation of genera in the subfamily Hydropsychinae (Trichoptera: Hydropsychidae). Aquatic Insects, 27 (2), 133 - 154." type="journal article" year="2005">Schefter (2005)</bibRefCitation>
report that the species lacks preanal appendages, but this was observed in a modified form. Like in other species in the 
<taxonomicName id="F38B09B71726A9099C0EFBBE7D78FB72" authorityName="Oláh &amp; Johanson" authorityYear="2008" box="[1028,1339,1141,1166]" class="Insecta" family="Hydropsychidae" genus="Hydromanicus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="verrucosus">
<emphasis id="06FFAE261726A9099C0EFBBE7D78FB72" box="[1028,1339,1141,1166]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Hydromanicus verrucosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group, the preanal appendages are shifted, or even pressed, to the median keel. In 
<taxonomicName id="F38B09B71726A9099C59FB567D4CFB4A" baseAuthorityName="Ulmer" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[1107,1295,1181,1206]" class="Insecta" family="Hydropsychidae" genus="Hydropsyche" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="seychellensis">
<emphasis id="06FFAE261726A9099C59FB567D4CFB4A" box="[1107,1295,1181,1206]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">H. seychellensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the 2 lobes, beside being pressed to the median keel, are also fused and are clearly visible.
</paragraph>
